04190nam a22005175i 9780773596252DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20142014xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735962527 a10.1515/97807735962522doi  a(DE-B1597)657637  a(OCoLC)875729568  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1032b.D83413 2014 7aHIS0060102bisacsh04a971.032231 aDucharme, Michel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Idea of Liberty in Canada during the Age of Atlantic Revolutions, 1776-1838 /cMichel Ducharme. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource :b3 tables, 1 diagram  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Ideas ;v6200tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tLiberty and Revolution in the Atlantic World -- tLiberty in the Province of Quebec, 1776–1805 -- tThe Birth of Reform Movements in the Canadas, 1805–1828 -- t“We, the people”: Republican Liberty in the Canadas, 1828–1838 -- tThe Primacy of Rights: Modern Liberty in the Canadas, 1828–1838 -- tCitizens, to Arms! The Rebellions of 1837–1838 -- tConclusion: Liberty As the Foundation of the Canadian State -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Idea of Liberty in Canada during the Age of Atlantic Revolutions, 1776-1838, Michel Ducharme shows that Canadian intellectual and political history between the American Revolution and the Upper and Lower Canada rebellions of 1837-38 can be better understood by considering it in relation to the broad framework of revolution in the Atlantic world between 1776 and 1838. Inspired by intellectual histories of the Atlantic world, Ducharme goes beyond the scholarly focus on Atlantic republicanism to present the rebellions of 1837-38 as a confrontation between two very different concepts of liberty. He uses these concepts as lenses through which to read colonial ideological conflict. Ducharme traces political discourse in both colonies, showing how the differing fates and influence of republican and constitutional notions of liberty affected state development. He also pursues a number of important revisionist historical claims, including the idea that nationalist politics were not at issue in the period and that "responsible government" was never a Patriote party platform or interest. Taking a wider view allows Ducharme to provide a solid understanding of the ideological substance of political conflict and shows that, starting in 1791, Canadian colonial political culture revolved around an ideal of liberty that differed from the liberty at work within the revolutionary movements of the late eighteenth century but was nonetheless born of the Enlightenment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / Pre-Confederation (to 1867).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311127407208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014z978311127709740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359625240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773596252423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773596252/original  a978-3-11-127407-2  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  a978-3-11-127709-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles